Title: Small Business Network: Insurance for Small Business!
Primary Event Type: z DO NOT USE-Business Legal & Personal Finance
Description: Can a business or individual afford not to have insurance should they suffer a catastrophic loss? On Tuesday, December 9th at 6:30pm, join us for an evening with James Hylton, Small Business Insurance Consultant, as he discusses the benefits insurance brings to the small business owner, the different types of coverage, risk minimization strategies and the relationship between the consumer and the insurer. Registration required (please see staff or phone 416-396-8951). Space is limited. James Hylton has ten years of experience working in the insurance field. He holds a Registered Insurance Broker Licence, Other than Life Licence, a Claims Adjusters Licence and two courses towards the Chartered Insurance Professional Designation. In addition to selling insurance, he was sales & service advisor for two different insurance companies before working as an underwriter in the personal lines and commercial sector.

Title: The Monkey Queen: Journey to the East
Description: Storyteller Diana Tso tells the story of "The Monkey Queen." In this twist on the legend of the Monkey King, Monkey Queen is born in the West and travels to the East in search of her ancestral roots. Diana Tso is a storyteller, performer, playwright and poet. A graduate of English Literature from the University of Toronto, Diana is also the artistic director of Red Snow Collective and has performed in theatres all over the world.

Title: Ask an Expert: Toronto Master Gardeners: Organic City Gardening
Description: Ask an Expert. What is organic city gardening and why should you care? Discover the basic principles of this increasingly popular gardening approach including the importance of soil, compost, mulch and water. Get the dirt on integrated pest management (IPM) including what it is and why you should use it. Learn about physical and biological controls: the organic chemical control of pests and weeds as well as organic control of plant disease. Toronto Master Gardeners will give you the scoop!

This program is brought to you by Malvern Family Resource Centre, Seniors Centre in collaboration with the Malvern Branch.

Title: Asian Heritage Month: East Asia and the Islands Homelands
Description: Head to Downsview for an afternoon of celebration of Homelands in East Asia and the Islands. 11:00 am - Kamishibai: The Art of Japanese Storytelling 'Kamishibai' which means "paper drama" is a form of storytelling accompanied by a sequence of story cards which are presented in a portable wooden 'theatre'. Presented by Joy Sato of Discover Japan. 1:00 pm - Sushi for the Soul! Sushi Making For The Soul is Toronto's most popular sushi making class, and weaves together the great art of sushi while raising awareness about the issues of seafood sustainability and food literacy for children. The class is lead by the award-winning writer, restaurateur and food literacy activist, Sang Kim. Registration required*. Space is limited! 3:30 pm - Filipino Fun! Join us for a traditional Filipino performance and the chance to learn or speak Tagalog, one of the most spoken languages of the Philippines. Presented by members of The Filipino Centre. Free! Please register for each program individually by calling 416-395-5720, e-mail doprograms@torontopubliclibrary.ca or by visiting the branch. *For any food allergy concerns, please speak to the presenter the day of. Toronto Public Library celebrates Asian Heritage Month with four mini-festivals celebrating culture and history from across Asia. Saturdays are Homelands Festival days, featuring dance, music, food, stories and literature.

Title: Kamishibai: The Art of Japanese Storytelling
Description: 'Kamishibai' which means "paper drama" is a form of storytelling accompanied by a sequence of story cards which are presented in a portable wooden 'theatre'. Originated in Japan in the 12th century, this became a popular method of storytelling between the 1920's into the 1950's. The kamishibai man would ride his bicycle from village to village to share his stories, announcing his arrival with the loud clapping of his wooden hiyoshigi. Kamishibai has enjoyed a revival in libraries and schools not only in Japan but around the world! Free! All ages welcome! Presented by Joy Sato of Discover Japan. Please register by calling 416-395-5720, e-mail doprograms@torontopubliclibrary.ca or by visiting the branch. Toronto Public Library celebrates Asian Heritage Month with four mini-festivals celebrating culture and history from across Asia. Saturdays are Homelands Festival days, featuring dance, music, food, stories and literature.

Title: Small Business Network: Insurance for Small Business!

On Tuesday, December 9th at 6:30pm, join us for an evening with James Hylton, Small Business Insurance Consultant, as he discusses the benefits insurance brings to the small business owner, the different types of coverage, risk minimization strategies and the relationship between the consumer and the insurer. Registration required (please see staff or phone 416-396-8951). Space is limited. James Hylton has ten years of experience working in the insurance field. He holds a Registered Insurance Broker Licence, Other than Life Licence, a Claims Adjusters Licence and two courses towards the Chartered Insurance Professional Designation. In addition to selling insurance, he was sales & service advisor for two different insurance companies before working as an underwriter in the personal lines and commercial sector.

Title: Celebrating Italian Heritage Month - "Three Women" Film Screening
Description: Hybrid identities that result from the merging of multiple cultures are becoming the norm in many contemporary pluralistic societies. "Three Women" from different generations discuss the personal changes that occurred after their immigration to Canada and explore how new identities emerged during the adaptation process. Jackie Rosati emigrated from Italy in 1932. She became a nurse and after the war she started a series of volunteer associations to help Italian immigrants. Gianna Patriarca immigrated to Canada in 1960. Although she began as a schoolteacher, she later became an accomplished writer and poet giving voice to Italian-Canadian women. Elena Basile expatriated in 1995 to pursue her Ph.D. While seeking to integrate herself in the Queer community, she discovered the challenges of Canada's multicultural diversity. By exploring changing modes of adaptation at three key historical moments in Canadian history, the documentary "Three Women" reveals how various challenges stimulated the women into crossing the boundaries that had held back many of their predecessors. The documentary "Three Women" ends with a series of questions about the meaning of adaptation in the new millennium. Join us for a special Q&A with Gianna Patriarca and Italian-Canadian film director and screenwriter, Adriana Monti after the screening of the documentary. In celebration of Italian Heritage Month! Contact the Downsview Branch for more programs and information about how this branch will be celebrating all things Italian for the month of June! Please register by calling 416-395-5720, e-mail doprograms@torontopubliclibrary.ca or visit the branch. Registration allows us to contact you if there are any program updates or cancellations.

Title: Mireille Messier
Description: César et son grand frère Jules ont mangé en cachette toute la salade prévue pour le dîner. Vite! Ils doivent en préparer une autre! Venez écouter Mireille Messier, l'auteure du nouvel album jeunesse "La salade de César", alors qu'elle nous raconte cette histoire croustillante! Partenariat avec Centre Francophone. Billets gratuits disponible 30 minutes avant le programme. One crouton at a time, César and his older brother Jules eat all the yummy salad that was meant for dinner. Now, they must quickly make another! Come listen to Mireille Messier, author of the new picture book "La salade de César", as she reads this silly story with all the right ingredients to make you laugh! In partnership with Centre Francophone. Free tickets available 30 minutes before programme.

Title: Small Business Network: Insurance for Small Business!
Primary Event Type: z DO NOT USE-Business Legal & Personal Finance
Description: Can a business or individual afford not to have insurance should they suffer a catastrophic loss? On Tuesday, December 9th at 6:30pm, join us for an evening with James Hylton, Small Business Insurance Consultant, as he discusses the benefits insurance brings to the small business owner, the different types of coverage, risk minimization strategies and the relationship between the consumer and the insurer. Registration required (please see staff or phone 416-396-8951). Space is limited. James Hylton has ten years of experience working in the insurance field. He holds a Registered Insurance Broker Licence, Other than Life Licence, a Claims Adjusters Licence and two courses towards the Chartered Insurance Professional Designation. In addition to selling insurance, he was sales & service advisor for two different insurance companies before working as an underwriter in the personal lines and commercial sector.

Title: Tante Caroline
Description: Les patentes de Madame Bidule! Tante Caroline se transforme en Madame Bidule. Elle invente, rafistole, crée, bricole des patentes et des trucs de toutes sortes. Sa curiosité et son humour font qu'elle ira jusqu'à chercher l'aide des jeunes du Club de lecture TD pour créer une histoire abracadabrante à partir de ses patentes. Une animation originale et interactive où les jeux de mots et la créativité sont à l'honneur! L'inscription n'est pas nécessaire. Miss Trinket has a problem: she invents, creates gizmos and widgets from all kinds of thing-amajigs but can't seem to finish her projects. She asks for help from the kids of the Summer Reading Club to create an incredible tale about her inventions. An original story where word play and creativity are honoured guests! No registration required.

Title: Small Business Network: Insurance for Small Business!
Primary Event Type: z DO NOT USE-Business Legal & Personal Finance
Description: Can a business or individual afford not to have insurance should they suffer a catastrophic loss? On Tuesday, December 9th at 6:30pm, join us for an evening with James Hylton, Small Business Insurance Consultant, as he discusses the benefits insurance brings to the small business owner, the different types of coverage, risk minimization strategies and the relationship between the consumer and the insurer. Registration required (please see staff or phone 416-396-8951). Space is limited. James Hylton has ten years of experience working in the insurance field. He holds a Registered Insurance Broker Licence, Other than Life Licence, a Claims Adjusters Licence and two courses towards the Chartered Insurance Professional Designation. In addition to selling insurance, he was sales & service advisor for two different insurance companies before working as an underwriter in the personal lines and commercial sector.

Title: Small Business Network: Insurance for Small Business!
Primary Event Type: z DO NOT USE-Business Legal & Personal Finance
Description: Can a business or individual afford not to have insurance should they suffer a catastrophic loss? On Tuesday, December 9th at 6:30pm, join us for an evening with James Hylton, Small Business Insurance Consultant, as he discusses the benefits insurance brings to the small business owner, the different types of coverage, risk minimization strategies and the relationship between the consumer and the insurer. Registration required (please see staff or phone 416-396-8951). Space is limited. James Hylton has ten years of experience working in the insurance field. He holds a Registered Insurance Broker Licence, Other than Life Licence, a Claims Adjusters Licence and two courses towards the Chartered Insurance Professional Designation. In addition to selling insurance, he was sales & service advisor for two different insurance companies before working as an underwriter in the personal lines and commercial sector.

Title: The eh List Author Series: Frances Itani - Tell
Event Type Option 2: z DO NOT USE Lunchtime Programs
Description: FRANCES ITANI, a Member of the Order of Canada, has received awards and accolades for her novels and for her poetry. In Tell, she brings to life post-war characters and situations which will not soon be forgotten by Canadian readers. Marriages battered by the havoc of war and the novelty of peacetime hold together by a thread. The question is, how much to tell?

Title: The Lifecycle of Stars
Description: Have you ever wondered where the stars came from? What are stars and how are they made? Using the latest images from space telescopes such as Hubble, Spitzer, and Herschel, Dr. Michael Reid (Dunlap Institute for Astronomy and Astrophysics) tells the story of how stars are born, live, and die, a cycle that has been playing out for nearly fourteen billion years. Stars form shrouded in clouds of gas and dust so thick that it's hard for us here on Earth to see what's happening. When they die, they die so quickly it can be hard to catch them in the act.

Title: Culture Days @ The Library: Nuno Felting with Nuriye Kilinc
Description: Nuno felts are non-woven fabrics adorned by a fibre artists and crafts enthusiast. The felting is extremely versatile to create a piece of art in fabric form. The technique often incorporates several layers of loose wool fibers combined to build up design elements, texture and color in the finished product. Participants in the workshop will experiment to create a lightweight scarf by laying few layers of loose fiber onto open weave silk fabric base. Space is limited to 20 participants only. Title: Small Business Network: Insurance for Small Business!
Primary Event Type: z DO NOT USE-Business Legal & Personal Finance
Description: Can a business or individual afford not to have insurance should they suffer a catastrophic loss? On Tuesday, December 9th at 6:30pm, join us for an evening with James Hylton, Small Business Insurance Consultant, as he discusses the benefits insurance brings to the small business owner, the different types of coverage, risk minimization strategies and the relationship between the consumer and the insurer. Registration required (please see staff or phone 416-396-8951). Space is limited. James Hylton has ten years of experience working in the insurance field. He holds a Registered Insurance Broker Licence, Other than Life Licence, a Claims Adjusters Licence and two courses towards the Chartered Insurance Professional Designation. In addition to selling insurance, he was sales & service advisor for two different insurance companies before working as an underwriter in the personal lines and commercial sector.

Title: MAP Family Saturdays - Black Creek Pioneer Village visits Agincourt

Title: Small Business Network: Insurance for Small Business!
Primary Event Type: z DO NOT USE-Business Legal & Personal Finance
Description: Can a business or individual afford not to have insurance should they suffer a catastrophic loss? On Tuesday, December 9th at 6:30pm, join us for an evening with James Hylton, Small Business Insurance Consultant, as he discusses the benefits insurance brings to the small business owner, the different types of coverage, risk minimization strategies and the relationship between the consumer and the insurer. Registration required (please see staff or phone 416-396-8951). Space is limited. James Hylton has ten years of experience working in the insurance field. He holds a Registered Insurance Broker Licence, Other than Life Licence, a Claims Adjusters Licence and two courses towards the Chartered Insurance Professional Designation. In addition to selling insurance, he was sales & service advisor for two different insurance companies before working as an underwriter in the personal lines and commercial sector.

Title: In Conversation with a Holocaust Survivor - CANCELLED
Description: This program features Hungarian Holocaust survivor Leslie Meisels, who will speak about his personal experiences during the Holocaust. Leslie Meisels was born in Nádudvar, Hungary in 1927. He lived with his parents, two brothers and both sets of grandparents. He survived the ghettos in Nádudvar and Debrecen, slave labour in Austria and the eventual deportation to Bergen-Belsen. He was liberated in April 1945 by the 9th US Army from a death train. His mother, father and both brothers also survived. Leslie immigrated to Canada in 1967.

Title: In Conversation with a Holocaust Survivor
Description: This program features Dutch Holocaust survivor Leonard Vis who will speak about his personal experiences during the Holocaust. Leonard Vis was born in Amsterdam in 1930. After the Germans occupied the Netherlands, his family went into hiding. They all survived and were liberated in 1945. After the war, Leonard served two years in the Dutch Army before moving to New York. Leonard came to Canada in 1967. Registration is required. Please call 416-395-5720 for more information or to register.

Title: Roy Henry Vickers and 'Lucky' Budd - Cloudwalker
Description: Roy Henry Vickers is one of Canada's best loved and honoured artists, with works spanning more than 4 decades. Robert 'Lucky' Budd is one of B.C.'s most important keepers of historical voices. Together, they bring to life the legend of Cloudwalker - How the Rivers were Made - with eloquent text and 17 new prints from Vickers. A perfect balance of story, image and message, this is a book for all generations. Items will be available for sale.

Title: Smart Investing With Toronto Star's Ellen Roseman
Primary Event Type: z DO NOT USE-Business Legal & Personal Finance
Description: Are you confused about how to save money and taxes when you invest? What is the difference between an RRSP and a TFSA (tax-free savings account)? Can you benefit from using a registered education savings plan (RESP) for your kids' post-secondary education? How about helping save money for a disabled family member with a registered disability savings plan (RDSP)? Ellen Roseman, a Toronto Star personal finance columnist, has followed investing for years and teaches courses at the University of Toronto's school of continuing education. She can explain the ins and outs of these plans, who should use them and how to make sure you follow the rules and don't get dinged for extra taxes. Registration required (please see staff in-branch or phone 416-396-8951). Space is limited.

Title: Small Business Network: Insurance for Small Business!
Primary Event Type: z DO NOT USE-Business Legal & Personal Finance
Description: Can a business or individual afford not to have insurance should they suffer a catastrophic loss? On Tuesday, December 9th at 6:30pm, join us for an evening with James Hylton, Small Business Insurance Consultant, as he discusses the benefits insurance brings to the small business owner, the different types of coverage, risk minimization strategies and the relationship between the consumer and the insurer. Registration required (please see staff or phone 416-396-8951). Space is limited. James Hylton has ten years of experience working in the insurance field. He holds a Registered Insurance Broker Licence, Other than Life Licence, a Claims Adjusters Licence and two courses towards the Chartered Insurance Professional Designation. In addition to selling insurance, he was sales & service advisor for two different insurance companies before working as an underwriter in the personal lines and commercial sector.

Title: Calligraphy

Skilled calligrapher, Kevin King will help participants to study and become familiar with how the pen works through learning the basic Italic alphabet and how to compose these letterforms into words and sentences. Title: Sales Skills for Entrepreneurs!
Primary Event Type: z DO NOT USE-Business Legal & Personal Finance
Description: Without sales, you have no business being in business, so knowing how to sell is essential for any entrepreneur. Join Small Business Coach, Patti Pokorchak, as she deconstructs her successful sales techniques so that anyone can sell more - faster and easier than ever. Learn the one crucial thing that all great entrepreneurs must master in order to succeed.... and it doesnt hurt at all! Registration required (please see staff or phone 416-396-8950). Space is limited. Patti Pokorchak is an award winning marketing and sales executive, with 30+ years of experience at IBM, Siemens, and many startup companies. Self-employed since 1992, she helped start and run a 7 figure software company for 10 years, before opening a thriving garden centre and destination hobby farm. Patti was not a born salesperson - she was a trained programmer, after dropping her quest to be an accountant - all great geeky careers. While at IBM, even after a gruelling two week residential sales course, she was still a nervous shy introverted sales person. Patti eventually overcame her shyness and loves to sell and has deconstructed her sales strategies to help other entrepreneurs and small businesses sell more effectively, with more skill and confidence.

Title: 10 Essential Habits for Joyous Health with Joy McCarthy
Description: Many people live their life feeling "okay" and assume that to live in health is simply to live in the absence of disease. Joy McCarthy (RNCP CNP) Holistic Nutritionist and author will share her personal wellness journey and inspire you to expect more...to expect joyous health! In this one-hour session, Joy will share her top 10 tips for leading your most joyous life ever! Learn the benefits of a healthy diet including the importance of key nutrients, smart food choices and key lifestyle habits to help you live joyously and feel fabulous. This eye-opening seminar will inspire you to eat and live well putting you on a permanent path to joyous health! Title: Hue: A Matter of Colour - National Film Board Mini Film Fest
Description: In honour of Black History Month, please join us for this free film screening at Agincourt Library. The feature documentary by renowned director and cinematographer Vic Sarin is a personal yet global investigation into the history and current state of colourism: the discrimination within one ethnicity based on differences in skin tone. Sarin travels the globe to discuss this complex cross-cultural social issue with individuals whose lives it affects. Hue leads viewers on a thoughtful and surprising journey to the heart of a painful and pervasive social issue that not only polices appearance, but also class, gender, and geography. No registration required. Film is 85 mins, unrated.

Title: The eh List Author Series: Bryan Prince - In Conversation
Event Type Option 2: z DO NOT USE Lunchtime Programs
Description: My Brother's Keeper chronicles the courage of former fugitive slaves who returned to the United States to enlist in the Union cause. Historian and author Bryan Prince from Buxton Ontario has created a gripping narrative which helps us understand why freed slaves left Canada in the 1860's to return to the United States, where they risked life, limb and liberty. Bryan speaks with author and critic Donna Bailey Nurse about his life, his work, and about his latest book.

Title: Amazing stories of 19th century African-Canadians in Toronto
Description: Hilary J. Dawson, historical researcher and popular speaker on Ontario African-Canadian history, will relate fascinating stories of the lives of some of Torontos 19th century African-Canadians. Stories of former slaves who became entrepreneurs opening blacksmith shops, barbershops, grocery and provisions stores, a hotel and Torontos first cab company. This presentation will look at the families of African descent who lived in Toronto and Etobicoke, the communities they lived in and the issues and challenges they faced. How were these exciting stories unearthed? Learn the secrets behind discovering the past from an expert.

Primary Event Type: z DO NOT USE-Business Legal & Personal Finance
Description: Since many business owners tend to ignore their websites, it's easy to stand out from your competition with a few simple changes. Discover how you can make small, ongoing improvements to your website that will make it a productive contributor to your bottom line! You'll learn: 1. Why your business should care aboutand invest inits website (hint: it doesnt take much to make a difference) 2. Proven tweaks that will yield BIG gains in the effectiveness of your content and messaging 3. Simple, actionable tips that will help you leverage the most important property in your online portfolio! Space is limited. Please phone 416-396-8950 or see library staff to register.

Title: The Disappearance of Indigenous Women: Whose Issue?
Description: Author Lee Maracle (U of T First Nations House) talks about the continuing violence against indigenous women--its origins and history in Canada's settlement--hitting on the apathy of the forces of justice and the resistance of the current government to conduct an inquiry. From the Pickton case, the Highway of Tears and the barbershop murders in B. C. to the RCMP study and the Native Women's Association research, she presents this a Canadian issue and calls on women to support only those parties who are prepared to conduct an inquiry. An International Women's Day event.

Title: Pan Am Program - Meet a Pan Am Athlete
Event Type Option 1: z DO NOT USE Pan Am Games
Description: Welcome Natalie Wideman, Team Canada Softball catcher! Natalie Wideman was a key player for the Junior Womens National Team in 2010 and 2011, and made the jump to the Senior team in 2012 after a fantastic sophomore season at California University of Pennsylvania. As a member of the Junior Womens National Team, Wideman played in the 2010 Pan American Qualifier in Colombia and also represented Canada at the 2011 ISF Junior Womens World Championship in South Africa. At the senior level, Wideman helped Canada to a fourth place finish at the 2012 ISF Womens World Championship in Whitehorse, Yukon and a silver medal at the Pan American Softball Championships in Puerto Rico in 2013. She was also a member of the 2014 Senior Women's National Team, notching three hits and driving in two runs in limited action at the ISF Women's World Championship in Haarlem, Netherlands. For more information please call the Agincourt Branch Children's Dept. 416-396-8952.

Title: Lessons from Immigrant Entrepreneurs
Primary Event Type: z DO NOT USE-Business Legal & Personal Finance
Description: Starting a business is never easy but doing it in a new country can be a real challenge! This session features a panel of immigrant entrepreneurs as they share their experiences starting businesses in Canada. The discussion includes: - How to find new customers - Overcoming cultural barriers - Where to find regulatory information - How to get help for your start-up The session is facilitated by the Entrepreneurship Connections team from ACCES Employment. Join us for a stimulating discussion about immigrant entrepreneurship! Free program. Space is limited. Please see Agincourt branch staff or phone 416-396-8950 to register.

Title: Golden Oak Author visits Downsview

Quinlan, a retired history teacher, has authored or coauthored thirty text books in the field of history. He is currently enjoying being a political activist in Toronto. This promises to be a lively and entertaining evening with a fascinating author.

Title: Celebrating the Stories of Chinese Canadian Women
Description: You're invited to a panel discussion to launch the photo exhibit, The Working Lives of Chinese Canadian Women, 1923-1967. This exhibit celebrates and explores the compelling work and life experiences of 20th century Chinese Canadian women with selected photographs from the website of the Multicultural History Society of Ontario, Chinese Canadian Women: 1923-1967. (www.mhso.ca/chinesecanadianwomen) Moderator: Kathryn Quan Panelists: Dora Nipp, Cultural Historian & Lawyer; CEO, Multicultural History Society of Ontario Valerie Mah, Educator & Historian, Project Contributor The photo exhibit will be on display at the Agincourt Library during Asian Heritage Month in May 2015. Free program. Space is limited. Please see Agincourt branch staff or phone 416-396-8950 to register.

Title: Small Business Network: Writing Effective Proposals!
Event Type Option 1: z DO NOT USE-Business Legal & Personal Finance
Description: Proposals are essential parts of business- more so in a tough economy. Successful proposals require planning, techniques, and the ability to write clear, persuasive and client-focused answers. This program will teach you how to plan, and structure your answers and how to improve your writing to create winning proposals. This program will also teach you how to: - Write effective covering letters and executive summaries - Improve the clarity of your writing for optimal impact - Write persuasive answers to RFP questions - Establish credibility and expertise - Break down questions and organize content - Customize each proposal, Create visual structure and format proposals for optimal results AND MORE! Free Program. Please see staff or phone 416-396-8950 to register. Space is limited.

Title: Author Reading - Velvet Haney reads from The Mousehouse Years: A Memoir

The Mousehouse Years recounts her parents' dysfunctional romance and how her single mother raised six children in the slums of Toronto in the early sixties. Yorkville Library, 22 Yorkville Avenue.
